# =============================================================================
# test-website/.htaccess — MyCovai (backup / troubleshooting reference)
# =============================================================================
#
# PURPOSE
# -------
# This folder is a small isolated test site. These rules do two things:
#   (1) Tell browsers and many proxies NOT to cache responses, so you almost
#       always see the latest PHP/HTML after you upload or deploy.
#   (2) Block direct HTTP access to /includes/ so only PHP can require those
#       partials (basic hygiene).
#
# WHY KEEP THIS FILE AS A "BACKUP"
# --------------------------------
# If the main site shows stale pages, mystery spinners, or odd caching after
# deploy, compare the live document root .htaccess to this one. The aggressive
# Cache-Control + FileETag None pattern here is a known-good baseline for
# "always fetch fresh" during debugging. You can copy ideas (not necessarily
# every line) into the root .htaccess temporarily, then revert once fixed.
#
# PRODUCTION NOTE
# ---------------
# For the full public site you usually want normal caching (browser + CDN) for
# performance. This file is intentionally harsh on caching — ideal for test and
# for short diagnostic windows, not as a permanent default for high-traffic pages.
#
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION A — Disable caching (requires Apache mod_headers)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Cache-Control: Combined directives tell clients "do not store a copy; if you
#   did, revalidate immediately; treat as expired now (max-age=0)."
# Pragma:        HTTP/1.0 fallback; some older clients respect it for no-cache.
# Expires: 0:    Marks content as already expired so caches should not serve it.
#
# If the server returns HTTP 500 after adding this block, the host may have
# disabled Header in .htaccess. Comment out the whole <IfModule mod_headers.c>
# block and retry; site should work without these headers (but caching returns).
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
<IfModule mod_headers.c>
	Header set Cache-Control "no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate, max-age=0"
	Header set Pragma "no-cache"
	Header set Expires "0"
</IfModule>

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION B — Turn off ETag generation for this directory
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Without ETag, Apache is less likely to answer "304 Not Modified" for small
# changes, so the browser fetches a full response more often. Pairs well with
# Section A when you need to confirm you are seeing the file you just uploaded.
#
# Rare: if AllowOverride does not permit FileETag, remove this line only.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
FileETag None

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION C — Block direct access to include partials
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Requests like https://example.com/test-website/includes/header.php should
# get 403 Forbidden, not raw PHP source as plain text (depending on server).
# RewriteRule flags: F = Forbidden, L = last rule (stop processing).
#
# Requires mod_rewrite (standard on cPanel/Apache). If rewrite is off, this
# block is skipped safely because of <IfModule mod_rewrite.c>.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
<IfModule mod_rewrite.c>
	RewriteEngine On
	RewriteRule ^includes/ - [F,L]
</IfModule>

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION D — Things .htaccess cannot fix (for your notes when "still stale")
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - Cloudflare (or another CDN): set cache rules / "Development Mode" for that
#   hostname; edge cache ignores your Apache Cache-Control if misconfigured.
# - Browser: hard refresh (Ctrl+F5) or a private window still helps sometimes.
# - PHP opcache: changing a .php file may need a few seconds or a PHP restart
#   on some hosts; not controlled by .htaccess.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# End of test-website/.htaccess
